Some serious training on customer service (soft skills) are crucial for this store (or maybe just for some employees)!!! It was my first time visiting downtown New York. I went inside to check out this place and buy a little snack before heading to the tour bus. My daughter, aunt and I decided to use the washroom, after travelling for such a long time.  We went in the line behind some other women. Then some others came along behind us, waiting for the washroom. Just then, a brown-skinned woman (or woman of colour) came over to the line, with an attitude, and body language with absolutely no customer service and said (I’m paraphrasing)  “this is not a public washroom, you can’t use the washroom if you’re not a customer.” I thought to myself, she can’t be talking to us. I continued to stand in the line. She came back around again with a loud voice saying “you can’t use the washroom. It’s for customers only. You have to pay for your food before you use the washroom. It’s written on the door. Now, I am a Canadian visitor and didn’t know the “policy”, and was planning to buy something but needed to use the washroom. What was the problem? How do you know if I’m a customer or not? How do you know if I’m buying something or not? Why didn’t you just ask me and the others in the line nicely if we were customers and explain what your policy was? In Toronto, Canada most restaurants would never treat foreigners like that, let alone our own citizens. Where was the customer service? I was APPALLED! I guess this is why visitors to Canada say “Canadians are so polite and nice.” I am a woman of colour as well, so it made me feel embarrassed and look bad as a woman of colour. No one should be treated this way. To make a long story short, I stood there with my daughter and relative, used the washroom, then bought a yogurt and a pineapple fruit cup. I spoke to the other employees at the counter  and explained how to treat customers when they walk into a store, that the treatment from the lady was unacceptable and rude. The sign on the washroom door doesn’t even say to pay before you use the toilet. Hmm! I pray and hope that the rest of the chain of stores « Prêt à manger » do not treat anyone like this one, because I will NEVER go back and I will tell other visitors to do the same.
